ercy, Saint-Lô, Manche, Basse-Normandie, Francie","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Francie"},"da":{"about 0980–1073":"omkring 0980–1073","0980–1073":"0980–1073","0982–Female":"0982–Afdød","1000–1050":"1000–1050","0945–Male":"0945–Afdød","0982":"0982","after 1050":"efter 1050","0980":"0980","1000":"1000","about 0980":"omkring 0980","1073":"1073","0945":"0945","1050":"1050","Kleingoeft, Bas-Rhin, Alsace, France":"Kleingoeft, Bas-Rhin, Alsace, Frankrig","Percy, Saint-Lô, Manche, Lower Normandy, France":"Percy, Saint-Lô, Manche, Basse-Normandie, Frankrig","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Frankrig"},"nl":{"about 0980–1073":"circa 0980–1073","0980–1073":"0980–1073","0982–Female":"0982–Overleden","1000–1050":"1000–1050","0945–Male":"0945–Overleden","0982":"0982","after 1050":"na 1050","0980":"0980","1000":"1000","about 0980":"circa 0980","1073":"1073","0945":"0945","1050":"1050","Kleingoeft, Bas-Rhin, Alsace, France":"Kleingoeft, Bas-Rhin, Alsace, Frankrijk","Percy, Saint-Lô, Manche, Lower Normandy, France":"Percy, Saint-Lô, Manche, Basse-Normandie, Frankrijk","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Frankrijk"},"en":{"about 0980–1073":"about 0980–1073","0980–1073":"0980–1073","0982–Female":"0982–Deceased","1000–1050":"1000–1050","0945–Male":"0945–Deceased","0982":"0982","after 1050":"after 1050","0980":"0980","1000":"1000","about 0980":"about 0980","1073":"1073","0945":"0945","1050":"1050","Kleingoeft, Bas-Rhin, Alsace, France":"Kleingoeft, Bas-Rhin, Alsace, France","Percy, Saint-Lô, Manche, Lower Normandy, France":"Percy, Saint-Lô, Manche, Lower Normandy, France","Normandy, France":"Normandy, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Mainfred","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an old Germanic personal name, usually said to be from <i>man</i> ‘man’ + <i>fred</i>, <i>frid</i> ‘peace’. However, it is more likely that the first element was <i>magin</i> ‘strength’ (the usual Norman form being <i>Mainfred</i>) or <i>manag</i> ‘much’. This name was in use among the Normans, who introduced it to Britain. However, it did not become part of the common stock of English given names, and was reintroduced from Germany in the 19th century. It was a traditional name among the Hohenstaufens, and was borne by the last  Hohenstaufen king of Sicily  (  1258–66 ), who died in battle against papal forces at Benevento. The name was also used by  Byron  for the central character in his poetic drama Manfred (  1817 ), a brooding outcast, tormented by incestuous love for his half-sister."],"variants":[{"name":"Manfried","meanings":["From an old Germanic personal name, usually said to be from <i>man</i> ‘man’ + <i>fred</i>, <i>frid</i> ‘peace’. However, it is more likely that the first element was <i>magin</i> ‘strength’ (the usual Norman form being <i>Mainfred</i>) or <i>manag</i> ‘much’. This name was in use among the Normans, who introduced it to Britain. However, it did not become part of the common stock of English given names, and was reintroduced from Germany in the 19th century. It was a traditional name among the Hohenstaufens, and was borne by the last  Hohenstaufen king of Sicily  (  1258–66 ), who died in battle against papal forces at Benevento. The name was also used by  Byron  for the central character in his poetic drama Manfred (  1817 ), a brooding outcast, tormented by incestuous love for his half-sister."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Count Of Caux and Poiters William Mainfred d'Perci was born about 0980, in Normandy, France as the son of Comt Rollo Thurston Brico de Perci. He had at least 1 son with Margaret. He died in 1073, in Kleingoeft, Bas-Rhin, Alsace, France, at the age of 94."},"et":{"about 0980–1073":"umbes 0980–1073","0980–1073":"0980–1073","0982–Female":"0982–Surnud","1000–1050":"1000–1050","0945–Male":"0945–Surnud","0982":"0982","after 1050":"pärast 1050","0980":"0980","1000":"1000","about 0980":"umbes 0980","1073":"1073","0945":"0945","1050":"1050","Kleingoeft, Bas-Rhin, Alsace, France":"Kleingoeft, Bas-Rhin, Alsace, Prantsusmaa","Percy, Saint-Lô, Manche, Lower Normandy, France":"Percy, Saint-Lô, Manche, Basse-Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"about 0980–1073":"noin 0980–1073","0980–1073":"0980–1073","0982–Female":"0982–Kuollut","1000–1050":"1000–1050","0945–Male":"0945–Kuollut","0982":"0982","after 1050":"1050 jälkeen","0980":"0980","1000":"1000","about 0980":"noin 0980","1073":"1073","0945":"0945","1050":"1050","Kleingoeft, Bas-Rhin, Alsace, France":"Kleingoeft, Bas-Rhin, Alsace, Ranska","Percy, Saint-Lô, Manche, Lower Normandy, France":"Percy, Saint-Lô, Manche, Basse-Normandie, Ranska","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Ranska"},"fr":{"about 0980–1073":"environ 0980–1073","0980–1073":"0980–1073","0982–Female":"0982–Décédée","1000–1050":"1000–1050","0945–Male":"0945–Décédé","0982":"0982","after 1050":"après 1050","0980":"0980","1000":"1000","about 0980":"environ 0980","1073":"1073","0945":"0945","1050":"1050","Kleingoeft, Bas-Rhin, Alsace, France":"Kleingoeft, Bas-Rhin, Alsace, France","Percy, Saint-Lô, Manche, Lower Normandy, France":"Percy, Saint-Lô, Manche, Basse-Normandie, France","Normandy, France":"Normandie, France","lifeSum